(44, 8, 19, 43, 5, 44, 44, 'Give me also this power', 'Seeking Honor and Power', 'This connection highlights the desire for power and recognition in both passages. In Acts, the request for power to bestow the Holy Ghost reflects a pursuit of honor, while John addresses the issue of seeking honor from one another instead of from God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 19, 64, 1, 9, 9, 'power', 'Desire for Authority and Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking power and authority. In Acts 8:19, the desire for the Holy Spirit''s power contrasts with Diotrephes'' ambition for preeminence in 3 John 1:9.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 19, 44, 8, 9, 11, 'Give me also this power', 'Connection of Sorcery and Power', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of power, as Simon seeks to obtain the ability to confer the Holy Spirit, similar to how he previously bewitched the people with sorcery. This connection highlights the contrast between true spiritual authority and deceptive practices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 19, 44, 8, 17, 17, 'lay hands', 'Connection of Holy Ghost Reception', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands to receive the Holy Ghost. The SOURCE verse expresses a desire for the same power seen in the TARGET passage, where hands are laid on individuals to impart the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 19, 46, 15, 8, 9, 'power', 'Power and Apostolic Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in the church. In Acts, the desire for power to impart the Holy Spirit contrasts with Paul''s humility about his apostolic role, acknowledging his past persecution of the church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 27, 5, 17, 17, 'the gift of God may be purchased', 'Value of Gifts and Rewards', 'This connection highlights the rejection of monetary gifts in both passages. Peter and Daniel both emphasize that divine gifts cannot be bought or are not to be exchanged for personal gain.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 40, 10, 8, 8, 'the gift of God may be purchased with money', 'Connection of Freely Given Gifts', 'This connection highlights the idea that the gifts of God cannot be bought with money, as emphasized in both passages. Acts 8:20 warns against the notion of purchasing divine gifts, while Matthew 10:8 states that these gifts are given freely.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 44, 2, 38, 38, 'the gift of God', 'Connection of God''s Gift', 'This connection highlights the nature of God''s gift, contrasting the idea of purchasing it with money in Acts 8:20 and the promise of receiving the Holy Ghost in Acts 2:38. Both passages emphasize the significance of divine gifts that cannot be bought.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 66, 18, 15, 15, 'the gift of God may be purchased with money', 'Connection of Wealth and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of wealth leading to destruction. Both passages emphasize the consequences of seeking riches, with Acts warning against purchasing God''s gifts with money and Revelation depicting merchants lamenting their loss.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 59, 5, 3, 3, 'the gift of God may be purchased with money', 'Connection of Wealth and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the negative view of wealth in both passages. Acts 8:20 warns against trying to purchase God''s gifts with money, while James 5:3 speaks of the corruption of gold and silver as a witness against the wealthy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 61, 2, 14, 17, 'the gift of God may be purchased with money', 'Connection of Covetousness and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of covetousness and the rejection of God''s gifts. In Acts, Peter warns against thinking that God''s gift can be bought, while 2 Peter describes those who forsake the right way for unrighteous gain.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 20, 12, 5, 15, 16, 'the gift of God may be purchased with money', 'Connection of Gifts and Money', 'Both passages emphasize the refusal to accept monetary gifts for divine blessings. In Acts, Peter rejects the idea that God''s gifts can be bought, similar to Elisha''s refusal of Naaman''s offerings in 2 Kings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 58, 4, 13, 13, 'heart is not right in the sight of God', 'Divine Insight into Hearts', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s awareness of human hearts. Both passages emphasize that nothing is hidden from God''s sight, indicating the importance of having a right heart before Him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 19, 36, 1, 1, 'heart is not right', 'Connection of Heart and Fear', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of the heart in relation to one''s standing before God. Acts 8:21 highlights a heart that is ''not right,'' while Psalms 36:1 indicates a lack of ''fear of God'' in the wicked''s heart.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 40, 6, 22, 24, 'thy heart is not right', 'Heart and Eye Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of one''s inner disposition. Both passages emphasize that a person''s true state, whether of heart or eye, determines their alignment with God or worldly pursuits.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'heart is not right', 'Heart and Love Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of a right heart in serving God. In Acts, a heart not right leads to exclusion, while in John, love for Jesus is essential for feeding His sheep.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 14, 25, 2, 2, 'heart is not right in the sight of God', 'Heart''s Condition Before God', 'Both passages emphasize the state of one''s heart in relation to God. Acts 8:21 states that a heart not right with God disqualifies one from participation, while 2 Chronicles 25:2 acknowledges doing right but not with a perfect heart.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 66, 2, 23, 23, 'heart is not right in the sight of God', 'Heart and Works Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of the heart and its relation to one''s actions. Acts 8:21 highlights a heart not right with God, while Revelation 2:23 speaks of searching hearts and rewarding according to works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 21, 66, 22, 19, 19, 'heart is not right in the sight of God', 'Connection of Divine Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment regarding one''s heart and actions. Both passages emphasize the consequences of being unworthy before God, with Acts 8:21 stating a heart not right with God and Revelation 22:19 warning against altering God''s words.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 55, 2, 25, 26, 'repent therefore of this thy wickedness', 'Connection of Repentance and Recovery', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of repentance for forgiveness and recovery from spiritual bondage. Acts 8:22 speaks of repentance for wickedness, while 2 Timothy 2:25-26 mentions God granting repentance to acknowledge the truth.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 27, 4, 27, 27, NULL, 'Repentance and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of repentance and the call to turn from wickedness. Both passages emphasize the need for individuals to break off their sins and seek forgiveness through righteous actions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 58, 4, 12, 12, 'thought of thine heart', 'Connection of Heart and Thoughts', 'This connection highlights the theme of the heart''s thoughts and intentions. Both passages emphasize the need for repentance and the discernment of one''s inner thoughts.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 40, 7, 7, 8, 'pray God', 'Connection of Prayer and Forgiveness', 'This connection highlights the importance of prayer in seeking forgiveness and receiving answers. Both passages emphasize the act of asking God, whether for forgiveness or for needs, suggesting a relationship between prayer and divine response.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 42, 11, 9, 13, 'pray God, if perhaps the thought', 'Connection of Prayer and Forgiveness', 'This connection highlights the importance of prayer in seeking forgiveness and receiving good gifts from God. Both passages emphasize the necessity of asking God for what one needs, including forgiveness and the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 44, 9, 11, 11, 'pray God', 'Connection of Repentance and Prayer', 'This connection highlights the theme of prayer and repentance. In Acts 8:22, the call to repent and pray is emphasized, while Acts 9:11 shows Saul actively praying, suggesting a transformation linked to repentance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 22, 44, 17, 30, 30, 'repent therefore of this thy wickedness', 'Call to Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of repentance. Acts 8:22 speaks of repentance for wickedness, while Acts 17:30 commands all men to repent, highlighting a universal call to turn from sin.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 20, 5, 22, 22, 'bond of iniquity', 'Connection of Iniquity and Bondage', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of iniquity, depicting it as a binding force. Acts 8:23 refers to being in the ''bond of iniquity,'' while Proverbs 5:22 describes being ''holden with the cords of his sins.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 23, 58, 6, 6, 'bond of iniquity', 'Connection of Bondage and Freedom', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of bondage and the need for liberation. Acts 8:23 speaks of being in the ''bond of iniquity,'' while Isaiah 58:6 discusses breaking ''every yoke'' and loosing ''the bands of wickedness.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 43, 8, 34, 34, 'bond of iniquity', 'Connection of Sin and Bondage', 'This connection highlights the theme of bondage to sin. In Acts 8:23, being in the ''bond of iniquity'' suggests a state of enslavement to sin, which parallels John 8:34''s assertion that ''whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 58, 12, 15, 15, 'gall of bitterness', 'Bitterness and Iniquity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of bitterness, with Acts referencing the ''gall of bitterness'' and Hebrews warning against a ''root of bitterness.'' This connection highlights the spiritual dangers associated with bitterness and iniquity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 56, 3, 3, 3, 'gall of bitterness', 'Connection of Bitterness and Iniquity', 'This connection highlights the themes of moral failure and the consequences of sinful behavior. Both passages emphasize the state of being trapped in negative conditions, such as ''gall of bitterness'' and ''living in malice and envy.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 5, 29, 18, 20, 'gall of bitterness', 'Bitterness and Iniquity Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the themes of bitterness and iniquity. Acts 8:23''s ''gall of bitterness'' directly echoes Deuteronomy 29:18''s ''root that beareth gall and wormwood,'' highlighting the consequences of turning away from God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 23, 5, 32, 32, 33, 'gall of bitterness', 'Bitterness and Poison Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of bitterness, with Acts referring to ''gall of bitterness'' and Deuteronomy describing ''grapes of gall'' and ''poison.'' This connection highlights a thematic link between the destructive nature of sin and its consequences.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 8, 24, 2, 8, 8, 8, 'Pray ye to the Lord for me', 'Appeal for Divine Intervention', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals seeking prayer or intercession to alleviate suffering. Both Simon and Pharaoh express a desire for relief from impending consequences, demonstrating a common human response to distress.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
